{
  "query": "How does rotational burning compare to leaving unburned patches during prescribed fires for butterfly populations in US prairies?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies from the USA, both rotational burning and leaving unburned patches during prescribed fires show benefits for butterfly populations in prairies, with some important differences:\n\n**Leaving Unburned Patches (Action 3879):** Studies show that the abundance of Karner blue butterflies increased over 2-3 years in oak savannas and prairies where unburned patches were left during prescribed burning. Six out of nine specialist butterfly species were more abundant at sites with unburned areas compared to sites without unburned areas, while one species was less abundant and two had similar abundance. Karner blue butterflies were recorded using all 11 unburned patches surveyed within oak savannas and prairies managed by burning.\n\n**Rotational Burning (Action 3883):** Multiple studies found that the total abundance of prairie specialist, grassland and all butterflies was higher on prairies burned more than one, two or four years ago than on prairies burned in the last one or two years under rotational burning management. The abundance of grassland and generalist butterflies was highest in the third year after burning, and migrant butterflies in the first year after burning. Two studies found that pine-oak barrens and prairies managed by rotational burning every 2-5 years had higher total abundance of butterflies than unmanaged sites. However, rotational burning showed mixed effects across different studies, with some finding lower abundance in rotationally burned prairies compared to unmanaged areas in certain regions.\n\n**Species-Specific Responses (Actions 3882, 3883):** Regal fritillary abundance was higher in grasslands managed by rotational burning every three years than on unmanaged sites, and abundance was higher in rotationally burned prairies four years after the last burn than one or eight years after. However, some studies found that regal fritillary and arogos skipper were less abundant in burned prairies compared to hayed prairies. Karner blue butterfly abundance was similar in rotationally burned and unmanaged oak savannas and prairies.\n\nBoth approaches provide refugia and recovery opportunities for butterfly populations, but timing since last burn appears critical for rotational burning effectiveness, while unburned patches provide immediate refugia during active burning periods.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3879",
    "3883",
    "3882"
  ]
}

