{
  "query": "What does the evidence say about the long-term success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation or captive-release?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on evidence from 16 studies evaluating butterfly and moth translocations and 13 studies evaluating captive-bred releases, the long-term success of re-establishing butterfly populations shows mixed results. For translocation programs within former range, eight studies reported that translocated populations persisted for 2-12 years and increased in abundance (Action 3909). However, three studies found that while some translocated populations persisted for 1-49 years and increased in abundance, other populations died out within 0-7 years (Action 3909). A review across the UK and Ireland found that only 25% of translocated and released captive-bred butterfly populations survived for at least three years, with 38% dying out within that timeframe, and only 8% surviving for more than 10 years (Action 3909). Another review reported that translocated large copper populations survived for up to 38 years but ultimately died out or required supplementation by further releases (Action 3909). For translocations outside known range, two of three studies reported populations persisting and increasing in abundance over 8 and 28 years, while one population died out within one year (Action 3911). For captive-bred releases, six studies reported populations persisting for 2-28 years and increasing in abundance, while two studies found populations died out after 1, 2, or 12 years or required further releases to survive (Action 3914). One study found that three of 10 captive-bred populations established, with at least one persisting for five years (Action 3914). A review found that 25% of captive-bred populations survived for more than 3 years, 38% died out within that time, and only 8% survived for more than 10 years (Action 3914). Released captive-bred caterpillars showed lower survival rates than wild or translocated caterpillars (Action 3914).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3909",
    "3911",
    "3914"
  ]
}

