{
  "query": "How do different methods of harvesting timber, such as selective logging and shelterwood harvesting, compare to clearcutting in their impact on moth diversity in US forests?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies conducted in the USA, different timber harvesting methods show varying impacts on moth diversity compared to clearcutting. For shelterwood harvesting, one controlled, before-and-after study found that species richness of macro-moths was higher after shelterwood harvesting than after patch-cutting or clearcutting, with richness similar to thinned and unharvested forests (Action 3871). Another replicated, controlled, before-and-after study found that shelterwood harvesting resulted in similar moth species richness to single tree harvesting, group selection harvesting, or clearcutting, but lower richness than unharvested forest (Action 3871). Additionally, moth species richness recovered faster after shelterwood harvesting than after group selection harvesting or clearcutting (Action 3871). For selective logging methods, one replicated, controlled, before-and-after study found that forests harvested by single tree selection had similar species richness of moths to forests managed by group selection harvesting or clearcutting, but lower species richness than unharvested forest (Action 3867). Regarding thinning practices, one controlled, before-and-after study found that species richness of macro-moths was higher after thinning than after patch-cutting or clearcutting, with richness similar to unharvested forest (Action 3868). For group selection harvesting, studies found similar species richness of moths to single tree harvesting or clearcutting, but lower richness than unharvested forest, with recovery rates similar to clearcutting but slower than shelterwood harvesting (Action 3868).",
  "action_ids": [
