  "query": "What are the documented effects of excluding different types of herbivores on butterfly and moth populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "The documented effects of excluding different types of herbivores on butterfly and moth populations show mixed but generally positive outcomes. For vertebrate herbivore exclusion, five of eight studies found that forest and grassland plots fenced to exclude or reduce the density of deer, sheep, pigs and large herbivores had higher abundance of butterflies, moths, caterpillars, rare macro-moths and New Forest burnet moths than unfenced plots (Action 3891). Two of four replicated studies found that forest plots fenced to exclude or reduce the density of non-native pigs and deer had greater species richness of butterflies and macro-moths than unfenced plots (Action 3891). However, two studies found that forest plots fenced to exclude elk had mixed effects on species richness and abundance of butterflies and arthropods including moths depending on fire intensity and year (Action 3891). One study found that grassland plots fenced to exclude elk had similar species richness and abundance of butterflies to unfenced plots in all years (Action 3891). A global systematic review found that reducing or removing grazing or browsing by wild or domestic herbivores in temperate and boreal forests increased the abundance of butterflies and moths but did not affect species richness (Action 3891). For survival and condition measures, all Glanville fritillary caterpillar nests survived in grassland fenced to exclude sheep compared to 88% in grazed areas, and fewer caterpillar nests were damaged in fenced areas (Action 3891). For invertebrate herbivore exclusion, one study found higher density of pearl-bordered fritillary butterflies at sites fenced to exclude grazing animals than at unfenced sites (Action 3885). Traditional grazing management showed that wet meadows managed by light grazing with cattle or horses had similar butterfly species richness and abundance compared to mowing management, but bog fritillaries showed lower numbers and reduced use of areas after cattle grazing began (Action 3971).",
