{"query": "In agricultural landscapes, how does restoring grassland from arable land compare to restoring grassland from abandoned meadows for butterfly communities?", "summary": "Based on the available evidence, grassland restoration from arable land generally shows positive outcomes for butterfly communities. Action 3929 found that grasslands restored from arable land developed butterfly communities that became increasingly similar to existing high-quality grasslands over the first 10 years after establishment, with 4-5-year-old created grasslands and abandoned cropland having greater species richness of butterflies than conventionally managed grassland or cultivated farms. Restored grasslands showed higher abundance of moths than conventional grassland and similar abundance to semi-natural grasslands. The effectiveness varied with establishment methods, with grasslands established by sowing grasses, legumes and forbs having higher species richness and abundance of butterflies than grass-only mixes.

Regarding abandoned meadows, Actions 3957 and 3956 provide evidence on cessation of management (mowing and grazing). Action 3957 found that grasslands abandoned for various periods (3-13 years, 10-20 years) generally had similar species richness of butterflies and moths to grasslands managed by mowing, though some studies found abandoned grasslands had lower abundance of all butterflies than mowed grasslands. Action 3956 showed that grasslands abandoned from grazing for 1-25 years had mixed results - some had higher abundance of butterflies and moths than grazed grasslands, while others had lower abundance or similar levels depending on the butterfly species and time since abandonment.

Action 3955 found that semi-natural grasslands restored by scrub clearance and reintroduction of grazing or mowing had different butterfly communities to existing species-rich grasslands and did not become more similar over time. However, direct comparative studies between restoration from arable land versus restoration from abandoned meadows were not identified in the evidence.", "action_ids": ["3929","3955","3957","3956","3908"]}

