  "relevant_summary": "Based on the documented evidence from action studies, prescribed fire in forest ecosystems shows both benefits and negative impacts for butterfly and moth populations. Benefits include: Three of four studies found that coniferous forest restored 1-2 years ago by burning (in combination with thinning) or burned once within the last 20 years had higher species richness of butterflies than unburned forest (action 3877). Two studies found that pine forest restored 1-2 years ago by burning (in combination with thinning) had higher abundance of butterflies than unburned forest (action 3877). The abundance of Karner blue butterflies increased over 2-3 years in oak savannas and prairies where unburned patches were left during prescribed burning (action 3879). Six out of nine specialist butterfly species were more abundant in pine barrens and prairies where unburned areas were left during prescribed burning compared to sites without unburned areas (action 3879). Negative impacts include: One study found that mixed forest and shrubland sites which had been burned the year before had similar butterfly species richness to unburned sites (action 3877). One study reported that in the spring after selective burning of eucalyptus forest there were fewer Eltham copper caterpillars than before (action 3877). The timing of prescribed burning affects outcomes, with one study finding that management of tropical savanna and floodplain with early season burning or no burning for 2-5 years increased caterpillar abundance, but management with late season burning did not (action 3878). Leaving unburned refugia appears beneficial, as Karner blue butterflies were recorded using all 11 unburned patches surveyed within oak savannas and prairies managed by burning (action 3879).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3877",
    "3878",
    "3879"
  ]
}

