{
  "query": "How do different methods of creating field margins in European farmland, such as uncultivated strips versus sown wildflower strips, compare in their effectiveness for butterfly communities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on evidence from European studies, sown wildflower strips consistently outperform uncultivated margins for butterfly communities in several key metrics. Sown wildflower strips had higher species richness and diversity of butterflies than conventional field margins, unsown margins, and cropped fields (action 3932). Eight of thirteen studies found sown wildflower strips had higher butterfly species richness and diversity than conventional field margins and unsown margins (action 3932). Additionally, ten studies found sown wildflower strips had higher abundance of all butterflies, generalist butterflies, and specialist butterflies than conventional field margins, unsown margins, and cropped fields (action 3932).\n\nIn direct comparisons, field margins sown with wildflowers had greater species richness and higher abundance of butterflies than grass-only field margins (action 3932). Two studies found that floristically enhanced grass buffers or wildflower strips had higher abundance of butterflies than uncultivated margins (action 3982).\n\nIn contrast, uncultivated margins showed mixed results compared to sown options. Two of five studies found that uncultivated margins had lower species richness or diversity of butterflies than margins sown with grasses and forbs or wildflowers (action 3981). Six of seven studies found that the abundance of butterflies and moths was lower in uncultivated margins than in margins sown with grasses, forbs, or wildflowers (action 3981). However, one study found the species richness of butterflies and day-flying moths was higher in permanent uncultivated margins than in sown fallow plots (action 3981).\n\nManagement factors also influence effectiveness - uncultivated margins that were not cut or were only cut in spring or autumn had higher species richness and abundance of butterflies than margins cut in summer (action 3981). Width was important for both margin types, with wider margins (up to 6m) showing greater species richness and abundance than narrower margins (actions 3981, 3982).",
