{
  "query": "What is the state of the evidence regarding the success of restoring habitats after mining and quarrying activities for butterfly and moth conservation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Four studies have evaluated the effects on butterflies and moths of restoring or creating new habitats after mining and quarrying, with two studies conducted in the Czech Republic, one in the UK, and one in New Zealand (Action 3862). The evidence indicates mixed results for restoration success. Community composition studies found that 15% of 380 invertebrate species (including 208 moth species) were only found on flattened spoil heaps, compared to 30% which were only found on unflattened heaps (Action 3862). Species richness was negatively affected by technical restoration, with technically restored quarries having lower species richness of butterflies and day-flying moths than quarries left to restore naturally, and flattened spoil heaps having lower moth species richness than unflattened spoil heaps (Action 3862). However, population abundance results were more positive, with one study finding that fertilized trees on slate waste tips had similar caterpillar abundance to unfertilized trees, and a restored peat bog after mining supported similar density and size of Fred the thread moth caterpillars compared to undisturbed bogs (Action 3862). No studies were found that evaluated the effects of protecting or restoring brownfield or ex-industrial sites specifically on butterflies and moths (Action 3835).",
